{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὑβρίζω</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 18.381, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>Doric dialect</i> <b>-ίσδω</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 14.9 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> <i>Attic dialect</i> <b>-ιῶ</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.221 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>], (ἐν-) probably in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 720 (-ίσεις codex R)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ὕβρισα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.87, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 560, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> ὕβρικα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 400, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.128 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>pluperfect</i> ὑβρίκειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 3.14 \">Refs</a>]:—<i>middle</i>, <i>future</i> ὑβριοῦμαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 666 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <i>future</i> ὑβρισθήσομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.222 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ὑβρίσθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 367, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 885a \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> ὕβρισμαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Cyclops” 665, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: (ὕβρις):—<b>wax wanton, run riot,</b> in the use of superior strength or power, or in sensual indulgence, ὑβρίζοντες ὑπερφιάλως δοκέουσι δαίνυσθαι κατὰ δῶμα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.227; ὑβρίζοντες ἀτάσθαλα μηχανόωνται 3.207, 17.588; ἀλλὰ μάλ᾽ ὑβρίζεις 18.381; ὁππότ᾽ ἀνὴρ ἄδικος καὶ ἀτάσθαλος.. ὑβρίζῃ πλούτῳ κεκορημένος 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 751; ἐνταῦθα νῦν ὕβριζε 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 82, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 480, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; especially of lust, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.30 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to σωφρονεῖν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Cyr.” 8.1.30, 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 4.4.2. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of over-fed asses, <b>neigh</b> or <b>bray and prance about,</b> ὑβρίζοντες οἱ ὄνοι ἐτάρασσον τὴν ἵππον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.129 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of horses, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 7.5.62 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of elephants, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 10.10. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> of plants, <b>run riot, grow rank and luxuriant,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 2.7.6, “CP” 3.15.4. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> <i>metaphorically</i>, of a river that swept away and drowned a horse, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.189 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; so γῆ ὕβριστο <b>had been carried away</b> by river-floods, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus (?) 154. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>transitive</i>, ὑ. τινά <b>treat</b> him <b>despitefully, outrage, insult, maltreat,</b> ἡμέας ὑβρίζοντες ἀτάσθαλα μηχανόωντο[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" (see. below 2) 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 11.695; ὑ. τοὺς ὑβρίζοντας χρεών 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 970; ὑ. γυναῖκα τὴν ἑαυτοῦ 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 4.15 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; με, ἐμέ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 840 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 1.4; τὰς νήσους 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 8.99: more frequently (especially in Prose) ὑ. εἴς τινα(s)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>commit an outrage</b> upon or towards him (them), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 620 (troch.), “Hipp.” 1073, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 899 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὑ. εἰς (uncertain reading) τοὺς θεούς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Nu.” 1506; εἰς σὲ καὶ τὴν σὴν γυναῖκα 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 1.16; εἰς τὰς πατρίδας 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 4.111; εἰς ταύτην τὴν παροιμίαν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 174b (_accusative_ to 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Sol.” 10, ὑ. τινά\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] was <b>to do one a personal injury,</b> ὑ, εἴς τινα <b>to injure that which belongs to one;</b> but the distinction was not observed): also ὑ. ἐν κακοῖσιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1612, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1151. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> frequently with <i>accusative</i> <i>cognate</i>, ὑ. ὕβριν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 880 (Lyric poetry); ὕβρεις 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 247; ὕβριν ἐς ἡμᾶς ὑ. [prev. author] “IA” 961, compare “Heracl.” 18; ὕ. ὑβρίζεις ἐπὶ θανοῦσι τοῖς ἐμοῖς [prev. author] “HF” 708; ὕβρεις ἃς κατὰ τὴν ἀγορὰν ὕβριζεν 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 22.68: with _neuter_ \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <i>adjective</i>, ὑ. τάδε <b>commit</b> these <b>outrages,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.118; ὑ. τἄλλα 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 400; ὅσα περὶ θεοὺς ὑ. τις 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 885b, compare 761e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: and with other Nouns, τῶν ἀδικημάτων.., τῶν ἐς Ἀθηναίους ὕβρισαν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.87 (so probably θεοὶ τεισαίατο λώβην, ἣν οἵδ᾽ ὑβρίζοντες ἀτάσθαλα μηχανόωνται (see. above 11.1) 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 20.170): and with double _accusative_, τοιαῦτα ὑ. τινά 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 613; τίνος δέ σ᾽ οὕνεχ᾽ ὕβρισ᾽ Αἴγισθος τάδ; 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 266, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 222a, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 6.4.2, “Cyr.” 5.2.28 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, ὕβριν ὑβρισθείς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 1297, compare 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 23.121; τάλαιν᾽ ἐγὼ τῆς ὕβρεος ἧς ὑβρίζομαι 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 1044; ὧν δ᾽ εἰς τὸ σῶμα ὑβρίσθαι φημί 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.25. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> in legal sense, <b>commit a physical outrage on one</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (ὕβρις 11.2,3), 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 14.26, 24.18, “fragment” 44, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.6 (_passive_), etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; so later, ἐμὲ δέ, ἐὰν δύνῃ, καὶ ὕβριζε καὶ ἄπαγε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PCair.Zen.” 454.9 (3rd c.BC),compare “PEnteux.” 79.7, +others (3rd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; γυναῖκες καὶ παῖδες ὑβρίζονται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.74; ὑβρισθῆναι βίᾳ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 874c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὰς γνάθους ὑβρισμένη <b>mauled</b> on the cheeks, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 903 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὑβριζομένους ἀποθανεῖν to die <b>of ill-treatment,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 3.1.13 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὑβρίσθαι <b>to be mutilated,</b> of eunuchs, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Cyr.” 5.4.35: of acts, τὰ ὑβρισμένα \">Refs</a>]<b>outrages,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 3.7. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> <i>perfect</i> <i>participle</i> <i>passive</i>, of things, <b>arrogant, ostentatious,</b> σημεῖ᾽ ἔχων ὑβρισμένα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 1112; στολὴ οὐδέν τι ὑβρισμένη 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 2.4.5. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5195","accentedUnicode":"ὑβρίζω","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5196","matchingForm":"ὕβρις","stepTransliteration":"hubris","gloss":"mistreatment","_zh_tw_Gloss":"傷損","_es_Gloss":"maltrato","_zh_Gloss":"伤损"},{"strongNumber":"G5197","matchingForm":"ὑβριστής","stepTransliteration":"hubristēs","gloss":"insolent man","_zh_tw_Gloss":"侮慢者, 侮慢人","_es_Gloss":"hombre insolente","_zh_Gloss":"侮慢者, 侮慢人"}],"shortDef":"to insult, mistreat","mediumDef":"to insult, mistreat <br /><b>to run riot;</b>, <i>transitive</i> <b>to outrage, to treat in an arrogant</b> or <b>spiteful manner, insult</b> <ref='Mat.22.6'>Mt. 22:6</ref>; <ref='Luk.11.45; 18:32'>Lk. 11:45; 18:32</ref>; <ref='Act.14.5'>Acts 14:5;</ref> <ref='1Th.2.2'>1Thess. 2:2</ref>*","stepGloss":"to mistreat","stepTransliteration":"hubrizō","count":5,"_es_Definition":"tratar vergonzosamente, insultar, maltratar","_zh_tw_Definition":"侮慢, 嘲弄, 惡待","_zh_Definition":"侮慢, 嘲弄, 恶待","_step_Type":"verb","_vi_Definition":"xúc phạm; sỉ nhục","_zh_tw_Gloss":"凌辱","_es_Gloss":"maltratar","_zh_Gloss":"凌辱"}]}